Default index types — the most-tested gotcha.

Pandas dataframes have a built-in row index. Spark dataframes do not — their rows have no inherent order. So pandas-on-Spark has to fabricate an index, whenever one is not provided. And the strategy it picks has both performance and correctness implications. There are three strategies, set with the compute default-index-type option.

The first is sequence. A single executor counts zero, one, two, and so on. It is sequential, so it matches pandas — but it triggers a non-distributed step, which makes it slow on large data.

The second is distributed-sequence, which is the current default. It is computed in parallel, using partition offsets. It is still sequential — the same numbers as pandas — with only a slight overhead. For most cases, this is the right answer.

The third is distributed. It uses monotonically increasing ids. It is the cheapest, and fully parallel — but it is not sequential. You get big gaps, like zero, one, then eight-point-five billion.

And that third one is the trap. Any code that depends on the exact index values — location-based lookups, joins on the index, or integer-location semantics — will silently break. This is the single most-tested fact about the pandas interface, so it is worth remembering.
